    content: `
      <h2>The U.S. Bankruptcy Code</h2>
      <p>The United States Bankruptcy Code provides several different chapters under which an individual or business can seek debt relief. The two most common chapters for individual consumers are Chapter 7 and Chapter 13. Understanding the fundamental difference between them is key to interpreting public bankruptcy records accurately.</p>
      
      <h2>Chapter 7: Liquidation</h2>
      <p>Chapter 7 is the most common and fastest form of bankruptcy. It involves the court-appointed bankruptcy trustee liquidating (selling) the debtor's non-exempt assets to pay off creditors. In return, the debtor receives a "discharge," which legally wipes out most unsecured debts, such as credit card balances and medical bills. The entire process is relatively quick, typically lasting only 3 to 6 months.</p>
      
      <h2>Chapter 13: Reorganization</h2>
      <p>Chapter 13 is designed for individuals with a regular, verifiable income who want to keep their major assets, such as a home facing foreclosure or a car. Instead of liquidating assets, the debtor proposes a structured 3- to 5-year repayment plan to pay back all or a portion of their debts to creditors, supervised by the court.</p>
      
      <h2>Public Record and Credit Implications</h2>
      <p>Both Chapter 7 and Chapter 13 filings are matters of public record and will appear on a person's credit report. A Chapter 7 filing remains on a credit report for 10 years from the filing date, while a Chapter 13 filing remains for 7 years from the filing date, reflecting the different nature of the debt resolution.</p>
    `
